<DOC><DOCNO> AP900222-0095 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-90 1217EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Kohl     02-22 0213</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Kohl,0218</SECOND><HEAD>Kohl's 10-Point Plan, Other Hits Now on Records andamp; Cassettes</HEAD><DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chancellor Helmut Kohl has assembledhis 10-point plan and other reunification hits in a long-playingrecord album and cassette tape offered free to the first 100,000East German fans.   The political hit parade takes listeners back to thechancellor's now famous speech to parliament Nov. 28, when he laidout the steps to unity.   ``What This Historic Hour Has Made Possible,'' the chancellor'sdebut album, also contains speeches during his visit to Dresden onDec. 19 and at the Brandenburg Gate on Dec. 22, when a stretch ofthe Berlin Wall was knocked out to join the two sides of thedivided city.   The albums and cassettes produced by the federal government areavailable while the supply of 100,000 lasts, free to East Germans.They were made at a cost of $90,000 to West German taxpayers.   On the bright blue record jacket, Kohl beams and waves over theroof of his Mercedes to well-wishers in Dresden during his Dec. 19visit.   According to Wolfgang Bergsdorf, head of the domestic departmentof the federal Press and Information Office, the album of Kohlspeeches being distributed during East German election campaignrallies ``is already a historical document.''</TEXT></DOC>